{
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "node-1774966923614",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# 2.3 Convergence Properties\r\n\r\naddition is random var: $Y = \\pm  1/\\sqrt{n}$\r\n\r\nit's expectation: $E[Y] = 1/2 \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{n}} - 1/2 \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{n}}$ = 0\r\n\r\nvariation: $Var(Y) = E[(Y - E[Y])^2] = E[Y^2]$ \r\n\r\n$E[Y^2] = 1/n$ as prob. that we see Y^2 is always 1\r\n\r\nNow for this \r\n$$\r\n\r\nW_n\\left(\\frac{i}{n}\\right) = W_n\\left(\\frac{i-1}{n}\\right) + \\frac{X_i}{\\sqrt{n}}, \\quad \\text{for all } i \\geq 1\r\n\\tag{sc01.f.1.1}\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n",
      "x": 1789,
      "y": 741,
      "width": 517,
      "height": 231,
      "nodeLabel": "N1"
    },
    {
      "id": "node-1774967027103",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# What's $E[W_n(1)]$  (here 1 means i=n) ?\r\n\r\n$$\r\nE[W_n(1)] = E[W_n((n-1)/n)] + 0 = E[W_n((n-2)/n) + 0] + 0 = ... = E[W_n(1/n)] = E[X_1/\\sqrt{n}] = E[Y] = 0\r\n$$ \r\n",
      "x": 2428,
      "y": 681,
      "width": 660,
      "height": 93,
      "nodeLabel": "N2"
    },
    {
      "id": "node-1774967125889",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# 2. What's $Var[W_n(1)]$ ?\r\n\r\n$$\r\nVar[W_n(1)] = Var(W_n(\\frac{n-1}{n}) + Y) = Var(W_n(\\frac{n-1}{n})) + 2 Cov(W_n(\\frac{n-1}{n}), Y) + Var(Y) = Var(W_n(\\frac{n-1}{n})) + 1/n = ... = 1/n + 1/n + ... = n \\cdot 1/n = 1 \r\n\r\n$$",
      "x": 2428,
      "y": 810,
      "width": 948,
      "height": 98,
      "nodeLabel": "N3"
    },
    {
      "id": "node-1774967393753",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# Let's prove (sc01.f.1.2)\r\n\r\n$$ \r\nW_n(i/n) = W_n(\\frac{i-1}{n}) + \\frac{X_i}{\\sqrt{n}} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{n}}\\sum_{k=1}^{i}X_k\r\n$$\r\n\r\nWhen we introduce some t not equal to 1: $t = i/n$ -> $i = nt$\r\n\r\nSo $$\r\nW_n(t) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{n}}\\sum_{k=1}^{nt}X_k = \\frac{\\sqrt{t}}{\\sqrt{nt}}\\sum_{k=1}^{nt}X_k = \\sqrt{t}(\\sum_{k=1}^{nt}\\frac{X_k}{\\sqrt{nt}})$$ \r\n\r\nand\r\n\r\n$$W_n(t) \\stackrel{d}{=} \\sqrt{t}\\cdot W_n(1)$$\r\n\r\nAs we know when $n \\rightarrow \\infty$ $W(1) \\sim N(0,1)$ \r\n\r\nso $$W_n(t)$$ is normally distributed for $X \\cdot \\sqrt{t}$ and it's variation is $t$ so $W_n(t) \\sim N(0, t)$\r\n",
      "x": 2428,
      "y": 932,
      "width": 753,
      "height": 240,
      "nodeLabel": "N4"
    },
    {
      "id": "node-1774967676570",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# 2.4 Formal Definition of Brownian Motion\r\n**Definition 2.2 (Brownian Motion):**\r\n\r\nThe process $W = (W_t : t \\geq 0)$ is a $\\mathbb{P}$-Brownian motion if and only if:\r\n\r\n**(BM.1)** $W_t$ is continuous in $t$, and $W_0 = 0$\r\n\r\n**(BM.2)** For any $t \\geq 0$, the value of $W_t$ is distributed under $\\mathbb{P}$ as a normal random variable $N(0,t)$\r\n\r\n**(BM.3)** For any $s, t \\geq 0$, the increment $W_{s+t} - W_s$ is:\r\n- Distributed as $N(0,t)$ under $\\mathbb{P}$\r\n- Independent of $\\mathcal{F}_s$ (the filtration/history up to time $s$)\r\n\r\n**Critical Point:** Condition (BM.3) is subtle and powerful. Many processes have marginal distributions $N(0,t)$ but are NOT Brownian motion. What makes Brownian motion special is that **all conditional distributions** maintain this structure.\r\n",
      "x": 854,
      "y": 1162,
      "width": 562,
      "height": 327,
      "nodeLabel": "N5"
    },
    {
      "id": "node-1774967765043",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# 2.3 Convergence Properties\r\n\r\n**At time $t=1$:** The process $W_n(1)$ is the sum of $n$ independent random variables, each with:\r\n- Mean: 0\r\n- Variance: $1/n$\r\n\r\nTherefore:\r\n- $\\mathbb{E}[W_n(1)] = 0$\r\n- $\\text{Var}(W_n(1)) = n \\cdot \\frac{1}{n} = 1$\r\n\r\n**Central Limit Theorem Application:**\r\n\r\nAs $n \\to \\infty$, the distribution of $W_n(1)$ converges to $N(0,1)$ (standard normal).\r\n\r\n**More generally at time $t$:**\r\n\r\n$$\r\nW_n(t) = \\sqrt{t}\\left(\\frac{\\sum_{i=1}^{nt} X_i}{\\sqrt{nt}}\\right)\r\n\\tag{sc01.f.1.2}\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThe term in brackets converges to $N(0,1)$, so $W_n(t)$ converges in distribution to $N(0,t)$.",
      "x": 854,
      "y": 663,
      "width": 564,
      "height": 377,
      "nodeLabel": "N6"
    },
    {
      "id": "node-1774967992411",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "---\r\n# 2.5 Remarkable Properties of Brownian Motion\r\n---\r\n",
      "x": 841,
      "y": 2388,
      "width": 468,
      "height": 80,
      "nodeLabel": "N7"
    },
    {
      "id": "node-1774968154793",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "### **(BM.2)** For any $t \\geq 0$, the value of $W_t$ is distributed under $\\mathbb{P}$ as a normal random variable $N(0,t)$\r\n\r\n\r\n Can you verify that $\\tilde{W}(t) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{c}} W(ct)$ satisfies (BM.2)? What's its variance at time $t$?\r\n\r\n---\r\nWe can do using fact that: $W_n(t) \\stackrel{d}{=} \\sqrt{t}\\cdot W_n(1)$: \r\n\r\n$W(ct) \\stackrel{d}{=} \\sqrt{ct}W(1)$, as $W(1) \\sim N(0,1)$ so $W(ct) \\sim N(0,ct)$, and $Var(W(ct)) = ct$\r\n\r\nSo we have:\r\n\r\n$$\r\nVar(\\tilde{W_t}) = Var(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{c}} W(ct)) = \\frac{1}{c} \\cdot ct = t\r\n$$\r\n",
      "x": 1884,
      "y": 1214,
      "width": 544,
      "height": 223,
      "nodeLabel": "N8"
    },
    {
      "id": "node-1774968529409",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# Challenge Question: Can you construct a process $X_t$ that satisfies (BM.1) and (BM.2) but fails (BM.3)?\r\n\r\n\r\n---\r\nHint: Think about $X_t = \\sqrt{t} \\cdot Z$ where $Z \\sim N(0,1)$ is a fixed random variable...\r\n---\r\n\r\n\r\nLet's consider $X_t = \\sqrt{t} \\cdot Z$, where $Z \\sim N(0,1)$\r\n\r\nBM.1: Continuity check: $X_0 = 0$ and X_t is continuous because Z and $\\sqrt{t}$ are both continuous - OK\r\n\r\nBM.2: $Var(X_t) = Var(\\sqrt{t} \\cdot Z) = t$ - OK\r\n\r\nBM.3: \r\n   - let's build process $Y_t = X_{s+t} - X_{s}$\r\n   - $E[Y_t] = E[\\sqrt{s+t} Z] - E[\\sqrt{s} Z] = 0$\r\n   - $Var(Y_t) = Var(\\sqrt{s+t} Z - \\sqrt{s} Z) = (s+t) - 2 \\sqrt{s+t}\\sqrt{s}\\cdot 1 + s = 2s+t - 2 \\sqrt{s (t + s)} = (\\sqrt{s} - \\sqrt{s+t})^2$ - it depends on s directly so doesn't satisfy BM.3 !\r\n",
      "x": 1884,
      "y": 1454,
      "width": 1034,
      "height": 265,
      "nodeLabel": "N9"
    },
    {
      "id": "node-1774968982374",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# Property 2.1 : Derivative of $W_t$\r\n\r\nAlthough $W$ is continuous everywhere, it is (with probability 1) differentiable nowhere. The path is infinitely \"jagged.\"\r\n\r\nWe know $W_t \\sim N(0,t)$, so $\\mathbb{E}[W_t^2] = t$. \r\n\r\nIf you tried to compute the \"derivative\" as: \r\n$$\r\n\\lim_{\\Delta t \\to 0} \\frac{W_{t+\\Delta t} - W_t}{\\Delta t}\r\n$$\r\n\r\nQuestion: What happens to the variance of this ratio as $\\Delta t \\to 0$\r\n\r\n- 1. $\\mathbb{E}[W_t^2] = Var(W_t) = t$ because of this :: variation: $Var(Y) = E[(Y - E[Y])^2] = E[Y^2]$\r\n- 2. $W(t+\\Delta t) - W_n(t) \\stackrel{d}= W(\\Delta t)$ because of additive property of BM process  \r\nso variation of\r\n$$\r\n    Var\\left(\\lim_{\\Delta t \\to 0} \\frac{W_{t+\\Delta t} - W_t}{\\Delta t}\\right) \r\n    = Var \\left( \\lim_{\\Delta t \\to 0} \\frac{W(\\Delta t)}{\\Delta t}\\right) \r\n    = \\lim_{\\Delta t \\to 0} Var \\left( \\frac{W(\\Delta t)}{\\Delta t}\\right)\r\n    = \\lim_{\\Delta t \\to 0} \\frac{1}{\\Delta t^2} \\Delta t = \\infty \r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n> The \"derivative\" has infinite variance - it doesn't converge to anything! This is why Brownian motion is nowhere differentiable.\r\n\r\n>Physical intuition: Brownian motion is \"too rough\" - it wiggles so violently at small scales that any attempt to measure a slope produces wild, unbounded fluctuations.  ",
      "x": 1542,
      "y": 1789,
      "width": 829,
      "height": 390,
      "nodeLabel": "N10"
    },
    {
      "id": "node-1774969094420",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# Property 2.2 : Unbounded range (hits any value eventually)\r\n\r\nStatement: Brownian motion will eventually hit any real value, no matter how large or how negative. \r\nIf $W_t = 1{,}000{,}000$, it will (with probability 1) return to zero at some later time.\r\n\r\nFormally, for any $a \\in \\mathbb{R}$: \r\n$$\r\n  \\mathbb{P}\\left(\\sup_{t \\geq 0} W_t \\geq a\\right) = 1 \\quad \\text{and} \\quad  \r\n  \\mathbb{P}\\left(\\inf_{t \\geq 0} W_t \\leq a\\right) = 1\r\n$$ \r\n\r\nEven more striking: if $W_t = 1{,}000{,}000$ right now, it will (with probability 1) return to zero at some later time.\r\n \r\n**Intuition**: At time $t$, we have $W_t \\sim N(0, t)$. As $t \\to \\infty$, the standard deviation $\\sqrt{t} \\to \\infty$. So the distribution \"spreads out\" without bound.\r\n\r\nMore precisely, for any level $a > 0$: \r\n$$\r\n\\mathbb{P}(W_t > a) = \\mathbb{P}\\left(\\frac{W_t}{\\sqrt{t}} > \\frac{a}{\\sqrt{t}}\\right) = 1 - \\Phi\\left(\\frac{a}{\\sqrt{t}}\\right)\r\n$$\r\n\r\nAs $t \\to \\infty$, we have $\\frac{a}{\\sqrt{t}} \\to 0$, so:\r\n$$\r\n    \\mathbb{P}(W_t > a) \\to 1 - \\Phi(0) = \\frac{1}{2}\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThis means at large times, there's roughly 50% chance of being above any fixed level!",
      "x": 1531,
      "y": 2253,
      "width": 842,
      "height": 350,
      "nodeLabel": "N11"
    },
    {
      "id": "node-1774969168086",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# Property 2.3: Instant Reccurence (once it hits a value, it hits it infinitely often)\r\n\r\nOnce Brownian motion hits a value, it immediately hits it again infinitely often, and continues to revisit it intermittently in the future.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
      "x": 1531,
      "y": 2676,
      "width": 837,
      "height": 107,
      "nodeLabel": "N12"
    },
    {
      "id": "node-1774969209790",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# Property 2.4: Self-Similarity (looks the same at all scales)\r\n\r\nBrownian motion looks statistically identical at all scales. Zooming in on any section reveals the same \"jaggedness\" - it never smooths out.\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n",
      "x": 1535,
      "y": 2834,
      "width": 833,
      "height": 112,
      "nodeLabel": "N13"
    },
    {
      "id": "node-1774971824430-0",
      "type": "file",
      "file": "Options/SC01_Continuous_Processes_Brownian_Motion.md",
      "x": -581,
      "y": 847,
      "width": 815,
      "height": 958,
      "nodeLabel": "M2"
    },
    {
      "id": "f1a2b3c4d5e60004",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# 3. Brownian Motion as a Stock Price Model\n\n### 3.1 Pure BM is Inadequate\n1. Mean zero: $\\mathbb{E}[W_t]=0$, but stocks grow over time\n2. Can go negative: $\\mathbb{P}(W_t < 0) > 0$ for all $t > 0$\n3. Constant absolute volatility ≠ real stocks\n\n### 3.2 BM with Drift\n\n$$ S_t = \\sigma W_t + \\mu t  $$\n\n$\\mathbb{E}[S_t] = \\mu t$, $\\text{Var}(S_t) = \\sigma^2 t$ — but still can go negative!\n\n### 3.3 Geometric (Exponential) Brownian Motion\n$$X_t = \\exp(\\sigma W_t + \\mu t) $$\n- **Always positive** ($\\exp > 0$)\n- Multiplicative log-normal returns\n- Proportional volatility: $dX_t/X_t$ has constant $\\sigma$\n- $\\sigma$ = log-volatility, $\\mu$ = log-drift",
      "x": 854,
      "y": 3101,
      "width": 734,
      "height": 359,
      "nodeLabel": "N17"
    },
    {
      "id": "f1a2b3c4d5e60005",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# 4. Introduction to Stochastic Calculus\n\n### 4.1 Why a New Calculus?\nBM is nowhere differentiable — zooming in reveals the same jaggedness (self-similar). We need calculus built from infinitesimal **Brownian increments** $dW_t$, not just $dt$.\n\n### 4.2 Stochastic Differentials\n$$dX_t = \\sigma_t \\, dW_t + \\mu_t \\, dt $$\nBoth $\\sigma_t$, $\\mu_t$ must be **adapted** to $\\mathcal{F}_t$ (no future information).\n\n### 4.3 Uniqueness\nSame $\\sigma_t$, $\\mu_t$, $X_0$ → identical processes. Coefficients are unique by **Doob-Meyer decomposition**.\n\n### 4.4 Stochastic Differential Equations\n$$dX_t = \\sigma(X_t, t) \\, dW_t + \\mu(X_t, t) \\, dt $$\nMay have no solution, multiple, or unique — harder than ODEs.",
      "x": 854,
      "y": 3637,
      "width": 742,
      "height": 280,
      "nodeLabel": "N18"
    },
    {
      "id": "f1a2b3c4d5e60006",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# 5. Itô's Formula: The Fundamental Theorem\n\n### 5.1–5.3 Why Chain Rule Fails\nIf chain rule worked: $W_t^2 = 2\\int_0^t W_s \\, dW_s$ → $\\mathbb{E}[W_t^2]=0$. But $\\mathbb{E}[W_t^2]=t \\neq 0$. ✗\n\n**Key result:** $(dW_t)^2 = dt$ (NOT zero!)\n$$\\int_0^t (dW_s)^2 = t \\quad \\text{(by WLLN)} $$\n\n### 5.4 Itô's Formula\nFor $dX_t = \\sigma_t dW_t + \\mu_t dt$ and $f \\in \\mathcal{C}^2$:\n$$dY_t = f'(X_t)\\sigma_t \\, dW_t + \\left[\\mu_t f'(X_t) + \\frac{1}{2}\\sigma_t^2 f''(X_t)\\right]dt$$\n**Multiplication rules:** $(dW_t)^2=dt$, $(dW_t)(dt)=0$, $(dt)^2=0$\n\n### 5.5 Examples\n- $d(W_t^2) = 2W_t \\, dW_t + dt$ → $W_t^2 = 2\\int_0^t W_s \\, dW_s + t$ ✓\n- $d(e^{W_t}) = e^{W_t}(dW_t + \\frac{1}{2}dt)$\n- GBM: drift is $\\mu + \\frac{1}{2}\\sigma^2$, NOT $\\mu$!",
      "x": 866,
      "y": 4096,
      "width": 808,
      "height": 311,
      "nodeLabel": "N19"
    },
    {
      "id": "f1a2b3c4d5e60007",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# 6. Solving Stochastic Differential Equations\n\n### 6.1 Doléans Exponential\nSDE: $dX_t = \\sigma X_t \\, dW_t$, $X_0=1$. Set $\\mu = -\\frac{1}{2}\\sigma^2$:\n$$X_t = \\exp\\left(\\sigma W_t - \\frac{1}{2}\\sigma^2 t\\right) $$\n\n### 6.2 General Geometric Brownian Motion\nSDE: $dX_t = X_t(\\sigma \\, dW_t + \\mu \\, dt)$, $X_0=x_0$:\n$$X_t = x_0 \\exp\\left(\\sigma W_t + \\left(\\mu - \\frac{1}{2}\\sigma^2\\right)t\\right)$$\n$\\mathbb{E}[X_t] = x_0 e^{\\mu t}$, always positive.\n\n### 6.3 Stochastic Product Rule\n$$d(X_t Y_t) = X_t \\, dY_t + Y_t \\, dX_t + \\sigma_t\\rho_t \\, dt $$\nExtra $\\sigma_t\\rho_t \\, dt$ from $(dW_t)^2=dt$. Vanishes for independent BMs.",
      "x": 854,
      "y": 4569,
      "width": 738,
      "height": 210,
      "nodeLabel": "N20"
    },
    {
      "id": "f1a2b3c4d5e60008",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# 7. Summary and Key Takeaways\n\n| Concept | Formula |\n|---|---|\n| Random walk | $W_n(i/n) = W_n((i-1)/n) + X_i/\\sqrt{n}$ |\n| BM at time $t$ | $W_n(t) \\to N(0,t)$ |\n| BM with drift | $S_t = \\sigma W_t + \\mu t$ |\n| Geometric BM | $X_t = \\exp(\\sigma W_t + \\mu t)$ |\n| Stochastic diff | $dX_t = \\sigma_t dW_t + \\mu_t dt$ |\n| **Key rule** | $(dW_t)^2 = dt$ |\n| **Itô's formula** | $df = f'dX_t + \\frac{1}{2}\\sigma_t^2 f'' dt$ |\n| Doléans exp | $\\exp(\\sigma W_t - \\frac{1}{2}\\sigma^2 t)$ |\n| GBM solution | $x_0\\exp(\\sigma W_t + (\\mu - \\frac{1}{2}\\sigma^2)t)$ |\n\n**Next:** SC-02 Change of Measure (CMG) → Martingale Representation → Black-Scholes",
      "x": 858,
      "y": 4953,
      "width": 742,
      "height": 355,
      "nodeLabel": "N21"
    },
    {
      "id": "f1a2b3c4d5e60009",
      "type": "text",
      "text": "# 8. Exercises for Practice\n\n**8.1** Prove $X_t = \\sqrt{t}Z$, $Z\\sim N(0,1)$ has marginals $N(0,t)$ but is NOT Brownian motion.\n\n**8.2** Show $X_t = \\rho W_t + \\sqrt{1-\\rho^2}\\tilde{W}_t$ (independent BMs) has $N(0,t)$ marginals. Is $X$ a BM?\n\n**8.3** Apply Itô's formula: find $d(\\exp(W_t))$.\n\n**8.4** Using product rule: find $d(W_t \\cdot e^{W_t})$.\n\n**8.5** Solve $dX_t = X_t(\\sigma \\, dW_t + \\mu_t \\, dt)$ for general $\\mu_t$.\n\n**8.6** Show $Y_t = \\log X_t$ satisfies $dY_t = \\sigma \\, dW_t + (\\mu - \\frac{1}{2}\\sigma^2)dt$ for GBM $X_t$.",
      "x": 854,
      "y": 5514,
      "width": 750,
      "height": 240,
      "nodeLabel": "N22"
    },
    {
